hose who abuse their powers in respect of persons who fall within the jurisdiction but do not satisfy the residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">and do not have independent means to access legal assistance, </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">would be</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">immunise</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> from the scrutiny of the courts.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> This is despite t</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">long recognition of </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">unimpeded access to the courts</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> to challenge the decisions of public bodies</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">as </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">right of fundamental importance.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> As a</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ccess to legal aid is </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">often </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a necessary precondition </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">for accessing the courts</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> limitations on legal aid must be proportionate and not frustrate the exercise of the fundamental right of access to justice. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The rationale for the changes in scope brought about by</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Off</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">enders Act 2012 </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">LASPO</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, and for the areas of work left in scope, was that only the most serious cases would be eligible for legal aid. Yet, within months of LASPO coming into effect this wide ranging </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> proposal would remove some of the very c</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ases that parliament said should </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">remain</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> in scope</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, including those</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> involving life, liberty, homelessness </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">and abuse of power by the state</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Introducing the</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> test is</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> therefore</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> directly contrary to the commitment given to parliament.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> discriminatory purpos</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">e and effect </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">of the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> also </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">make</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> it contrary to Article 14 of the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR) when read together with the other Articles of the ECHR engaged by the litigation in question. Article 14 provides that the enjoyment o</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">f the rights contained in the Convention shall be provided without discrimination or grounds of race, religion or sex. It has been interpreted as to include a person’s place of residence. Article 18 on the Treaty of the European Union prohibits discriminat</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ion based on nationality, as does Article 4 of Regulation 883/2004,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Article 21 Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union and Article 24 Directive 2004/38.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The residence proposal would fall foul of those provision</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s as</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> UK nationals are more likely </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">to satisfy </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">the test </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">than non-nationals. In addition, the proposal is likely to lead in many cases to violations of the UK's positive obligations to investigate and prevent breaches of Articles 2, 3, 4 and 8 of the ECHR and to breaches of the right to </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">access the courts under Articles 5 and 6 ECHR.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The G</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">overnment </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">state</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> that anyone excluded </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">from legal aid </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">by the residence test c</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> apply for exceptional </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">funding. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">However</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, t</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">he exceptional </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">category is a discretionary one, with wide scope afforded to t</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">civil servant </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">decision maker. We expect decisions on such a fundamental matter as access to the courts to be governed by detailed regulation not subject to discretion,</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> as relying on discretion to enforce a constitutional right is “to shift the foundati</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ons of freedom from the rock to the sand”.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">There </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">is also </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a specific problem with the proposed </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> in the context of human rights claims as claims under the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Human Rights Act 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> must ordinarily be </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">commenced within 12 months of the events givin</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">g rise to the claim. It is proposed that migrants must accrue 12 months lawful residence before they are eligible for legal aid. That will mean in many cases by the time they are eligible </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> legal aid, they will be statute barred from bringing a claim</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Disproportionate </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">i</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">mpact </span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The Government has provided various exceptions to the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">including </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">sylum seekers,</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">victims of trafficking, detention cases, children’s and S</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">pecial </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">mmigration </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ppeals </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ommission</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> cases</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">which they believe </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ensure the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">fulfil</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ment of the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">human rights obligations</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">These e</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">xception</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s, however,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> do not</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> protect some of the most vulnerable people in society. For example, the asylum seeker exception does not </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">extend to people who have been refused asylum or where a</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">n individual is granted some form of lesser protection, such as humanitarian protection. It is trite law to state that a refused asylum applicant is entitled to bring a fresh claim. Under the proposals, an asylum applicant would only have assistance with t</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">heir first application. Women asylum applicants are likely to suffer the greater impact of this restriction as victims of abuse, such as sexual or domestic violence, are often reticent in disclosing their history. Thus, a victim of sexual violence may fail</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> to disclose the true detail of their experiences with the result that their claim is refused. Such a person, who may succeed eventually in putting forward her case fully, would be deprived of legal aid. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Moreover, the residency threshold would likely imp</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">act most severely on the homeless and destitute who are awaiting a decision from the Home Office on their status in the UK. It can take the Home Office years to make a decision and many of their refusals are overturned on appeal after long delays. All the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">while, the immigrant’s freedom to access the courts to challenge even the most egregious abuses is </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">restricted</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> as they are unable to access legal aid</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Housing and community care, including homelessness cases, would be particularly adversely affected as again many of the persons who would be caught up in related litigation would not satisfy the test. For example, in </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (Clue) v Birmingham CC</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> a destitute </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Jamaican national with dependent children successfully challenged the local authority’s refusal to provide her and her children with support pending the determination of their application for leave to remain. The Court of Appeal held that to deny support w</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ould contravene the best interest</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> of the children and their</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> human</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> rights to </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">respect for their </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">private and family lives. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">While the Government has conceded that children under the age of one year will not be required to have 12 months lawful residency to apply for legal aid, they must still be lawfully resident in the UK when applying for legal aid. This does not fit easily w</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ith the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">obligation under the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Children Act 1989</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> to safeguard and promote the welfare of children. The impact of the proposal concerning children moved internationally would also be profound.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">In summary,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> parties in cases of the following types would all face considerable difficulties obtaining legal aid:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Respondents in 1980 Hague Convention cases who have ‘fled’ to this jurisdiction or moved here with no sufficient connection to the UK</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Applicants in stat</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">es not signatory to the 1980 Hague Convention seeking a return of children th</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ere in wardship proceedings</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Stranded spouses who have be</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">en here for less than 12 months</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Applicants for contact on an application made pursuant to Article 12 of the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">1980 Hague Conv</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ention</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Applicants for recognition made pursuant to the provisions of Brussels </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">II</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">revis</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">f)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Applicants for recognition and enforcement of a foreign order under the 1980 Hague Convention. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Unintended consequences</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The unintended consequence of fundamental importance to the Government is that implementing the residence test proposal is likely to increase costs for the Ministry of Justice </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">both in the L</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">AA</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and the courts</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, other Government departments and local authori</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ties. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Denying access to legal aid through the residence test would </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">further contribut</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> to the rising number of </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">litigants in person, creating significant additional costs for the courts.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The c</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ourts and the Home Office are also likely to face additional costs </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">because the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">qualifying period for lawful residence for successful asylum applicants begin</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> on the date of the asylum application</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">his denies successful asylum seekers who have their</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> asylu</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">m claim</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">approv</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ed within 12 months of submission</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> access to legal aid</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, thus </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">creat</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a perverse incen</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">tive </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">for asylum seekers </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">encourage, where possible, delays which will enable them to meet the 12</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">month threshold. This</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> will </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">inevitably see</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> taxpayer funds </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">meeting increased legal </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">and court costs</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Research has also suggested that the test could cost local authorities up to £26</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">million annually</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. This is because</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> local authorities will still be required to provide assistance </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">to pursue legal issues </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">to those </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">they support, such as unaccompanied migrant children</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. Costs </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">will also be created for local authorities who will be required to support those made homeless or destitute due to their inability to pursue their legal issues without access to legal aid</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> This m</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">eans that instead of saving the public purse, implementing the residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> will at the very least simply </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">shift costs to local authorities,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and may even increase </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> taxpayer’s</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">burden</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Ref367281606"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The residence proposal would impede access to the court</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s, would be discriminatory and breach the well-established principle of equality. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">If implemented i</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">t would have</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a disproportionate impact on vulnerable groups in society</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">would represent a radical departure </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">from the principle of access to justice</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">by plac</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ing a </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">complete bar on persons who fall under the jurisdiction of the courts of England and Wales from obtaining legal aid. Finally, there is a strong likelihood that the provision would be </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">in violation of </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">both European law</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">LASPO</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span></a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Prison law</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_Ref367281612"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Overview </span></a></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Prisoners are inherently vulnerable to human rights abuses as a result of their dependent position in a state-run and closed environment. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The Government believes that the existing prisoner complaints process and the Prison and Probation Ombudsman provide </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">sufficient protection of prisoner human rights, but there is conflicting evidence on th</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">e accessibility</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and cost</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> of these services</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">We believe that t</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">he Government’s proposal to withdraw access to legal advice and assistance from prisoners in the vast </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">majority</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> of instances would, if enacted, have a devastating and widespread impact on the ability of prisoners to enforce their rights. This not only threatens the rights of individual prisoners, but also the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">operation of the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">wider prison system. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Implicat</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ions for </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">h</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">uman </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">r</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ights</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">risoners retain all of those</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> human </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">rights not expressly taken from them or by necessary implication.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> Foremost amongst those retained </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">human </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">rights is a right of access to the Courts.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> If that right is to be one of substance it must encompass an entitlement to access proper legal advice in order that prisoners’ cases can be put before the Courts on an even footing</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">; t</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">here must be equality of arms with the state.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> The effect of the propos</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ed reforms, which is to deprive prisoners of access to a lawyer in all but a very limited class of case, is to impair the very essence of the right of access to the Courts. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The G</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">overnment’s proposals purport, by implication, to ring-fence cases within th</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">e ambit of Articles 5 and 6 of the ECHR, such as Parole Board applications and prison adjudications, but not cases engaging other Convention articles. There is no logical reason for this. The exclusion of actions arising from, for example, Article 8 rights</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> will </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">mean that prisoners are unable to challenge the failures to provide resettlement packages designed to assist </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">them </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">to reintegrate and rehabilitate on release, which is a key part of government strategy.</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Moreover, the G</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">overnment’s attempts to safegua</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">rd cases within the ambit of Articles 5 and 6 are ill thought out and do not achieve what they s</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">et out to do. For example, the G</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">overnment proposes to safeguard matters affecting a prisoner’s progress</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ion through his or her sentence (for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">through the</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> completion of offending behaviour courses</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, but purports to exclude a prisoner from seeking specialist advice on his suitability for treatment in a Dangerous an</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">d Severe Personality Disorder (DSPD</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">) Unit. In fact</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> such decisions impact substantially upon se</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ntence progression, not least because DSPD treatment takes many years to complete, which may extend the period of imprisonment significantly. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Ref367281643"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Equally, the proposal to exclude categorisation</span></a><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> cases from scope ignores the fact that the question of categori</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">sation is intrinsically linked to sentence progression and therefore to liberty. It has long been recognised that a Category A prisoner serving an indeterminate sentence has no realistic prospect of release until the Secretary of State has downgraded </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">them</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> Accordingly</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> such decisions are within the broad ambit of Article 5, and in any event touch upon liberty. However, the Ministry of Justice has not granted any oral hearings to determine complex questions of suitability for Category A in the years 2008 – </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">2013 </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">with the exception of 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> By contrast several oral hearings have been directed by Court orders following applications for judicial review. This exemplifies why proper access to lawyers on matters such as categorisation, amongst other things, is a</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">n integral part of safeguarding prisoners’ rights.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Unintended c</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">onsequences</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The removal of a prisoner’s entitlement to legal aid for all matters relating to his or her treatment in prison is liable to discourage the maintenance of a humane prison system th</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">at promotes and safeguards human rights. It would be naïve to suppose that the system always works as it is intended to, or that serious breaches of human rights do not occur in the prison system. Recent cases reported in the media, most notably a female p</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">risoner kept in segregation in an “unkempt and squalid” cell for five years, confirm this reality.</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Ultimately, the issue is not simply that individual prisoners may be </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">unable to access a lawyer to challenge </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">decisions, but rather </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">how </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">the arbitrary limitation of access to legal assistance </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">would impact the nature of the wider prison system</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Judicial review</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_Ref367281665"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Overview </span></a></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Judicial review is one of the main ways in which violations of human rights can be litigated and the compatibility of </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">legislation with the ECHR can be tested.</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Threatening the viability of carrying out judicial review work will therefore have serious consequences for access to justice and the ability of individuals to uphold their human rights by challenging the actions </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">and/or decisions of public bodies.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Implications for human r</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ights</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Judicial review </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">is particularly suited to achieving the main object of a</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> claim of a human rights breach. A</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s Woolf LCJ explained in </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Anufijeva v LB Southwark</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">:</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">“Where an infringement of an </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">individual's human rights has occurred, the concern will usually be to bring the infringement to an end and any question of compensation will be of secondary, if any, importance. This is reflected in the fact that, when it is necessary to resort to the cou</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">rts to uphold and protect human rights</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, the remedies that are most frequently sought are the orders which are the descendants of the historic prerogative orders or declaratory judgments</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. The orders enable the court to order a public body to refrain from or</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> to take action, or to quash an offending administrative decision of a public body.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The orders described in this passage must be sought by judicial review</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, meaning j</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">udicial review claims cover the whole field of susbtantive and procedural human rights. A</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">nything which make</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> it unviable for practitioners to bring claims for judicial review or which discourages them from doing so will likely impede access to justice and the ability to take action to prevent human rights violations. We have no doubt that the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">proposals will have this inhibiting effect. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The original suggestion was that legal aid would only be paid where the claimant had actually been granted permission. It is now proposed that this should be the general rule but that that there should be a dis</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">cretion to pay legal aid where a case has concluded according to exhaustive criteria</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> In substance this leaves the original proposal untouched. The criteria are so exacting that they will rarely be met and since they trigger a discretion only</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> there will </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">be no practical way to enforce payment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Disproportionate i</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">mpact</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The proposal creates an unacceptable level of risk for practitioners and will force many of them either not to take on this kind of work or not to take cases that are in any way challenging </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">or uncertain. There are several factors that lead us to this conclusion</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">An application for permission carries a relatively high risk of initial failure. Even where a claim is meritorious it is often necessary to persist to an oral hearing or further to obtain permission. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">For example, while </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Wood v Commissioner of Police</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> is now</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> a leading case on privacy and police records, p</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ermission</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> for judicial review</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> was only granted on appeal. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Judicial review claims are “front loaded” in </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">that most of the work from the c</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">laimant’s perspective must be done at the stage of brin</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ing the claim. Practitioners therefore have to invest a large amount of time, cost and effort for which they may not get paid. This is increased still further if they have to proceed to an oral hearing or appeal. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Applications for permission are difficult </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">to predict and there is much variability among judges</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Many cases settle on beneficial terms after issue but before permission. It is not possible to tell how these are reflected in the statistics. Under the proposals these cases would not be paid for </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">except on a discretionary basis.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Although legal aid practitioners have a better than average record in obtaining permission</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">and in securing a positive outcome for their clients</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">many are already operating in marginal conditions and will find the risks </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">too great to continue. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">This is likely to have a</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> disproportionate impact on </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">black and minority ethnic (</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">BME</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">arristers</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> due to the fact that the majority of j</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">udicial </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">eview</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> cases are </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">immigration cases and BME barristers </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">are over-represented </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">in this area of l</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">egal practice</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">A particularly damaging part of the proposal is that it penalises practitioners by refusing payment </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">where the c</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">laim settle</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> before permission</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">with a benefit to the client. It is often difficult to obtain a costs order in these cases. The M</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">inistry of Justice</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> proposes that there should be a power to pay but for reasons already given that will be ineffective. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Even if permission is refused that does not mean that the claim ought not to have been brought. Often claims become academic or the me</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">rits change when the authority produces late disclosure. In other cases the refusal simply shows that the judge disagreed with the argument and not that it was misconceived. If lawyers have to bear all of these risks without being paid then </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">many</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> will stop </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">doing the work altogether.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Unintended c</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">onsequences</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The current proposal increases the incentive </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">local authorities </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">fail to engage or to provide important information when they ought to because authorities may be able to “starve out” claimants because their lawyers will have to give up before issuing </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">proceedings. The proposal rewards bad practice by </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">those </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">public bodies </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">least likely to comply with their duties under the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Human Rights Act 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">If the Ministry of Justice is determined to penalise practitioners by making retrospective decisions not to pay them for work they have done then this should only apply </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">where they have brought proceedings improperly. There is a ready mechanism to decide this since judicial review proceedings can now be declared to be wholly without merit if permission is refused. This is intended to block an application for oral renewal b</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ut could also be adapted for legal aid purposes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Borderline cases </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_Ref367281678"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Overview </span></a></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The Government proposes to remove from the scope of the civil legal aid scheme the small residual group of cases </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">which can presently be publicly-</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">funded even if the prospects of </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">success can only be assessed as ‘borderline’ (i.e. no greater than 50%).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Many of the cases within the present residual group raise human rights issues. The latest available statistics (see </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">para</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">51 below</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">) show two </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">main </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">classes of case: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ases which involve the prospect of a loss of a person’s home </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> engaging the human right to respect for the home (‘</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ousing’ cases)</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:7.33pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ases which involve the prospect of the loss of a person’s children into the care system </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> engaging the right to respect for family lif</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">e (‘</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ublic law children’ cases)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Of all the measures in the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> proposals, this one is therefore likely</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> to have the most immediate and adverse effect on human rights. Yet, it is proposed that it be brought into force later this year under secondary legislation even before the JCHR has had an opportunity to conclude its own scrutiny of the measure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Implicat</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ions for human rights </span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">It has only been possible to litigate human rights cases in the domestic courts for the past 12 years. The development by the courts of human rights jurisprudence and guidance is in its infancy. In cases raising issues of principle o</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">n human rights it is therefore often impossible to predict the likely outcome with certainty. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The classic illustration was the resolution of the question whether, in a claim for possession of a person’s home, their human right to respect for that home co</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">uld qualify or trump the claimant’s rights in property law. Resolving that question required three successive cases to be financed by legal aid through the entire judicial system</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">culminating in three successive decisions of the House of Lords</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> The Lords w</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ere divided in all three cases </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">and the position remained unclear until yet a further case, financed throughout on legal aid, settled the matter unanimously in the Supreme Court as recently as 2011</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> in the case of </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pinnock</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref32"></a><a href="#_ftn32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> All this litigation was only capab</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">le of being pursued because the protection of the home was recognised as so important that funding was made available even though the occupiers’ representatives could, for obvious reasons, never say that prospects of success were greater than ‘borderline’.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">This example illustrates a further point. Had legal aid not been available for those cases, and had not the domestic courts been led by them to the conclusion reached in </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Pinnock</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, the UK Government would have been required by the Strasbourg Court to repea</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">tedly pay compensation to those evicted without consideration of their human rights as demonstrated by </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Connors v UK</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref33"></a><a href="#_ftn33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> McCann v UK</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref34"></a><a href="#_ftn34">[34]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Kay v UK</span><a name="_ftnref35"></a><a href="#_ftn35">[35]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Buckland v UK</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref36"></a><a href="#_ftn36">[36]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> In short, the modest legal aid spend on borderline cases (estimated at a maximum </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">annual spend </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">of £1</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">illion</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">) saved an outpouring of costs and compensation payable by the UK Government in respect of repeated infringements of this aspect of human rights. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">This</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> is but one example.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Disproportionate i</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">mpact </span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">In its response to the initial consultation proposal, the Bar Council advanced the proposition that any rational system which invited an assessment of merits by reference </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">to the </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">prospect of success had to take account of the class of case in which even a q</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ualified and experienced assessor, armed with all the relevant facts and with no further lines of enquiry, could not</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> for good reason</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">put the case in a ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">likely to win</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">’ or ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">likely to lose</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> category.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Most cases assessed as be</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ing in the ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">borderline</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> categor</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">y do </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">not</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> presently qualify for help from legal aid. But the present criteria recognise that some cases are of such importance to the legal aid applicant that public funds must be made available to ensure access to justice and the rule of law, even if no cl</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ear assessment can be made of the likely outcome of the case. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">That fact does not do any damage to public confidence in legal aid. Such cases will ensure access to justice where something really important is at stake. Every reasonable member of the public</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> will have expected there to be a small cluster of cases which proved unsuccessful – the price to be paid for ensuring the protection of the rights of individuals where no precise assessment had been possible on the win-lose prospects spectrum.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Unintended</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> consequences</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The consultation proposal, as initially formulated, was to cease funding the residual group of cases in order to save an estimated £1</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">illion</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. But it was not backed by any data or detail.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">To make any sensible evaluation of the proposal, one n</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">eeded empirical data showing, for a significant past period:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">How many cases were assessed as borderline but nevertheless received legal aid funding?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">In what classes of case did this occur?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">How many of those cases produced a benefit for the client (and cos</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ts recovery)?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">How many were actually lost and what did they cost?</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> And,</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">What, if any, are the common features of those that won/lost?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Ref366830153"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Recently, in response to the criticism that the proposal ha</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> not initially been informed by such data, the Ministry of Justice published a short table simply identifying the subject matter of the borderline cases concluded in a single year.</span></a><a name="_ftnref37"></a><a href="#_ftn37">[37]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p s