 number of cases funded in each category, which cases succeeded (in whole or in part) or why those that failed were unsuccessful. Confining the data to a single year makes it impossible to derive anything useful from</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> it. Many of the responses to the initial consultation focussed on the absence of an informed case for the change. The Government response to that point, and the limited material it has published, fails to </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">address</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> criticism</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">In short, the categories </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">of case which now get legal aid, even if assessed as borderline, are tightly defined and are, quite properly, not generously drawn. They are, by definition, only the most significant types of cases for the individuals concerned.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Like many other respondent</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s, the Bar Council </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">argued</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> that the proposal, if implemented, will not achieve any savings at all. The reasons for this were threefold: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Instead of making sensible and reasoned assessments (i.e. that the prospects cannot be precisely measured) where the pr</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ospects are genuinely unclear, it will be necessary to err on the side of caution and assess at 51% where (as in all such cases presently falling into the scheme) something really important is at stake</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Decisions by the Director of Legal Aid which put the p</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">rospects of success to be just less than 50% will lead to more appeals to Adjudicators</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> therefore tying up additional resources, and</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">More applications will be made for legal aid at the investigatory level to enable a more precise assessment of prospects </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> success, </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">building in additional cost and, often more importantly, delay.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">This will at best</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> be revenue neutral, </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">and could likely lead to additional cost to the legal aid fund</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and, ultimately, the taxpayer</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. The only guaranteed result will be that many case</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s which hitherto deserved to get legal aid funding will no longer do so even though about h</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">alf would have been successful. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The Government’s response acknowledges these points but singularly fails to make a decent rejoinder to them.</span><a name="_ftnref38"></a><a href="#_ftn38">[38]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> £1 million from no longer funding borderline cases, £4</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">illion</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> from changes to criminal legal aid for prison law and £1-3</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">illion</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> for placing judicial review work at risk. The Government has not calculated projected savings for introducing a residence test due to lack of data. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Transforming legal aid: next steps </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">(2013), Ministry of Justice, Annex B: Response to consultation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Tran</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">sforming legal aid: scope, eligibility and merits (civil legal aid): Impact assessment</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">IA No: MoJ194</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> (2013), page 6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ex parte Khawaja</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [1984] AC 74 at 111G-112A</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (Medical Justice) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2011] EWCA Civ 1710 quashe</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">d immigration removal policy as “unlawful because it abrogated the constitutional right of access to justice” and found that “in order to have effective access to the courts, the person served with removal direction…needs to have a reasonable opportunity t</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">o obtain legal advice and assistance”. See also </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (Evans) v Lord Chancellor</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2012] 1 WLR 838, paragraph 25 (Laws LJ): “For the state to inhibit litigation by the denial of legal aid because the court’s judgement might be unwelcome or apparently damaging wo</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">uld constitute an attempt to influence the incidence of judicial decisions in the interests of government. It would therefore be highly inimical to the rule of law.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">D</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">v</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [1978] AC 171, 239G: </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">“And</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> if it comes to the forensic crunch...it must be law, not di</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">scretion, which is in command”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scott v Scott</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [1913] AC 417, 477</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid: delivering a more credible and efficient system </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">(2013), Ministry of Justice, paragraph 3.56</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Transformi</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ng legal aid: next steps </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">(2013), Ministry of Justice, Annex B: Response to consultation, paragraphs 125-126</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2010] EWCA Civ 460</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> Section 22(3)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> Section 55</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Wright v Michael Wright Supplies and Anor</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2013] EWCA Civ 234, (Ward LJ): “[S]aving expenditure</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> in one public department in this instance simply increases it in the courts. The expense of three judges of the Court of Appeal dealing with this kind of appeal is enormous…With more and more self-represented litigants, this problem is not going to go awa</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">y…[J]ustice will be ill served indeed by this emasculation of legal aid.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Transforming legal aid: next steps </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">(2013), Ministry of Justice, Annex B: Response to consultation, paragraph 133</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn15"></a><a href="#_ftnref15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Executive Summary: Shadow Impact Assessments </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">(2013), No Recourse </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">to Public Funds Network. Available at: </span><a href="http://www.nrpfnetwork.org.uk/policy/Pages/default.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nrpfnetwork.org.uk/policy/Pages/default.aspx</span></a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn16"></a><a href="#_ftnref16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Transforming legal aid: next steps </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">(2013), Ministry of Justice, Annex B: Response to consultation, paragraphs </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">37</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">-43</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn17"></a><a href="#_ftnref17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Raymond v Honey </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">[1983] 1 AC 1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn18"></a><a href="#_ftnref18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (Daly) v SSHD </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">[2001] 2 AC 532</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn19"></a><a href="#_ftnref19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">De Haes v Belgium </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">(1997)</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">25 EHRR 1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn20"></a><a href="#_ftnref20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Rehabilitation – a revolution in the way we manage offend</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">ers</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> (2013), Ministry of Justice</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn21"></a><a href="#_ftnref21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">Prisoners are categorised A-D according to risk, with A being for highly dangerous prisoners, and D being suitable </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">for an open prison</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn22"></a><a href="#_ftnref22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (Williams) v SSHD </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">[2002] 1 WLR 2264</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn23"></a><a href="#_ftnref23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">Response to Freedom of Information Request by the Ministry of Justice, 26 June 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn24"></a><a href="#_ftnref24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Report on an Unannounced Inspection of HMP Bronzefield</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">, which described this treatment as “cruel, inhumane and degrading”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn25"></a><a href="#_ftnref25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> S</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">ee </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The Impact of the Human Rights Act on Jud</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">icial Review: An empirical study</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> (2003), Public Law Project</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn26"></a><a href="#_ftnref26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2004] 2 WLR 603, [53]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn27"></a><a href="#_ftnref27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review: Proposals for further reform</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> (2013), Min</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">istry of Justice, paragraph 125</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn28"></a><a href="#_ftnref28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2010] 1 WLR 123</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn29"></a><a href="#_ftnref29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> The impact assessment to the current proposal suggests that</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> this is not lower than 18% and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">probably much higher</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> It is not possible to be precise because much data is missing, but legal aid case outcomes only record actual refusals in some 25% of cases.</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> See also </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Court Statistics Quarterly January to March 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> (2013), Ministry of Justice, page 48.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn30"></a><a href="#_ftnref30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> This submission draws directly on the experience and knowledge of one of the very few Queen’s Counsel specialising in housing cases raising human rights issues and who has undertaken many ‘borderline’ cases</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn31"></a><a href="#_ftnref31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">London Borough of Harrow v Qazi</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2003] UKHL 43; </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Kay v London Borough of Lambeth</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2006] UKHL 10; and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Doherty v Birmingham City Council</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2008] UKHL 57</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn32"></a><a href="#_ftnref32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Manchester City Council v Pinnock</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2011] UKSC 6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn33"></a><a href="#_ftnref33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2004] ECHR 223</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn34"></a><a href="#_ftnref34">[34]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2008] ECHR 385</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn35"></a><a href="#_ftnref35">[35]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> [2010] ECHR 1322</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn36"></a><a href="#_ftnref36">[36]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:10pt">[2012] ECHR 1710</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn37"></a><a href="#_ftnref37">[37]</a>